The project has made significant progress in achieving the result. The following key points summarize the progress:1.Development of Strategic Plans: Two strategic plans have been developed/revised, including the Strategic Plan Implementation Strategy for Punjab Assembly and the 1st draft of the Balochistan Strategic Plan. These plans have enhanced the capacity for budgetary oversight and representation within the respective assemblies, providing a roadmap for effective governance and aligning assembly goals with constituents needs.2.Policy Dialogue and Participation: A policy dialogue was conducted, with the attendance of 126 parliamentarians from different houses. This inclusive dialogue increased understanding of budgetrelated matters, the state of the economy, and Pakistans debt challenges among participants. The dialogue fostered more informed decisionmaking, improving budgetary allocations and economic planning.3.Beneficiary Briefings and Legislative Acts: Beneficiaries were briefed on social issues and relevant laws, including Women Inheritance Law, Hindu Marriage Act, and Human Trafficking Act. The project supported legislative acts that provided legal protection, addressed gender equality, religious minority rights, and human trafficking. The drafting of Acts in all houses is an ongoing process, contributing to meeting international obligations.4.Improved Parliamentary Processes: The project enhanced the effectiveness of parliamentary processes and representation of diverse perspectives. Parliamentarians knowledge and skills were improved in areas such as legislative assessment, postlegislative scrutiny, delegated legislation, and representation. This progress aligned legislative drafting practices with international best practices, promoting transparency, accountability, and inclusivity.5.National Conference on SDGs: The national conference on Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) served as a platform for interassembly exchanges and discussions. Representatives from all assemblies and diverse stakeholders participated, promoting collaboration, shared learning, and addressing national and provincial priorities.6.Capacity Building for Stakeholder Engagement: Activities and workshops enhanced parliamentarians capacity to engage with media, civil society organizations (CSOs), and other stakeholders. Parliamentarians actively participated, improving their communication skills, transparency, and partnerships. Womens representation in these initiatives reflected the commitment to gender equality and active participation in legislative processes.7.Gender Analysis Toolkit: A Gender Analysis Toolkit was developed and piloted to improve the capacity of parliamentary committees and women parliamentary caucuses in addressing genderrelated concerns. The toolkit provided practical guidance for conducting gender analysis, promoting gender mainstreaming, and integrating a gender lens into policy development and legislative processes. It contributed to addressing gender, inclusiveness, and minority rights in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Punjab, and Sindh Provincial Assemblies.The progress made in these areas collectively contributed to the enhanced legislative, oversight, budgetary, and representation capacity, promoting effective governance, transparency, accountability, inclusivity, gender equality, and human rights in the legislative process.

The VRI is a composite measure composed of a broad basket of indicators grouped into three categories which is designed to enable updated crosscomparison and vulnerability tracking despite inconsistent and often out of date data availability. The VRI process is multistage engaging both IPs and communities in the setting of an initial score. First the CAR conducts a review of available secondary data seeking out information which speaks to any of the listed indicators. Next the list of indicators is reviewed for gaps if any of the three categories noted above are too sparsely populated with secondary data points additional primary research is carried out by Community Listeners qualitative researchers and community members selected from the programming areas. The number of Community Listeners per township is dependent on the demographic characteristics of the township and is aimed at providing full coverage of different ethnic or religious communities. Generally primary data collection is limited to 10 key informant interviews KIIs per Township per Community Listener using purposive sampling to ensure adequate demographic diversity of participants. Responses are cleaned translated from local languages to English and analysed at which point they can be made to serve as indicator data points or supplementary data to existing data points.

Specifically, Indicator 7.1.1 refers to the proportion of population with access to electricity. This is expressed in percentagefigures and is disaggregated by total, urban and rural access rates per country, as well as by UN regional and global classifications.
